{"title_page": "Long Train Runnin'", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Refimprove|date=July 2011}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Long Train Runnin'\n| cover      = Long Train Runnin 1973.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[The Doobie Brothers]]\n| album      = [[The Captain and Me]]\n| B-side     = Without You\n| released   = 1973\n| format     = [[7\" single]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     = [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Studios]], [[North Hollywood, Los Angeles|North Hollywood]], California<ref>{{Cite AV media notes|title= The Captain and Me |others= The Doobie Brothers |year= 1994 |url= https://www.discogs.com/release/2297992-The-Captain-And-Me/images |accessdate= August 16, 2016 |type= liner notes |publisher= [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]}}</ref>\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country rock]]<ref>{{cite web|first= Chelsey |last= Stuyt |title= The Doobie Brothers' 'Southbound' a Jukebox of Greatest Hits |work= Vancouver Weekly |date= November 17, 2014 |accessdate= April 28, 2019 |url= https://vancouverweekly.com/doobie-brothers-southbound-jukebox-greatest-hits/}}</ref>\n| length     = 3:25\n| label      = [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n| writer     = [[Tom Johnston (musician)|Tom Johnston]]\n| producer   = [[Ted Templeman]]\n| prev_title = [[Jesus Is Just Alright#The Doobie Brothers' version|Jesus Is Just Alright]]\n| prev_year  = 1972\n| next_title = [[China Grove (song)|China Grove]]\n| next_year  = 1973\n}}\n\n\"'''Long Train Runnin''''\" (or \"'''Long Train Running'''\") is a song recorded by [[The Doobie Brothers]] and written by band member [[Tom Johnston (musician)|Tom Johnston]]. It was included on the band's 1973 album ''[[The Captain and Me]]'' and released as a single, becoming a top 10 hit on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], peaking at No. 8.\n\nIt was [[Cover version|covered]] by Italian band Traks in 1982 and then by English [[girl group]] [[Bananarama]] in 1991. In 1993 the Doobie Brothers version was [[remix]]ed and charted again in several countries, including reaching No. 7 in the [[UK Singles Chart]].\n\n==Origin==\nThe tune evolved from an untitled and mostly ad-libbed jam that the Doobies developed onstage years before it was finally recorded. Its working title, according to Johnston, was \"Rosie Pig Moseley\" and later \"Osborn\". \"I didn't want to cut it,\" Johnston later confessed. \"...I just considered it a bar song without a lot of merit. Teddy [Templeman], on the other hand, thought it had some.\" Templeman convinced Johnston to write words to the song.\n\nJohnston performed the lead vocal and the rhythmic guitar strumming that propels the song.\n\n==Charts==\n;Original release\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1973)\n!Peak<br/>position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite book|first= David |last= Kent |authorlink= David Kent (historian) |title= Australian Chart Book 1970-1992 |publisher= Australian Chart Book |location= [[St Ives, New South Wales|St Ives, N.S.W.]] |year= 1993 |page= 92 |isbn= 0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|58\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadaadultcontemporary|20|chartid=4849|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|8|chartid=4840|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|64|artist=The Doobie Brothers|song=Long Train Runnin'|songid=233289|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|12|artist=The Doobie Brothers - Long Train Runnin'|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|10|artist=The Doobie Brothers|song=Long Train Runnin'|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}\n|-\n|New Zealand (''[[New Zealand Listener|Listener]]'')<ref>{{cite web|title= flavour of new zealand \u2013 search listener |website= Flavour of New Zealand |accessdate= June 12, 2018 |url= http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=search%20listener&qartistid=868#n_view_location}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|15\n|-\n|